<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="tree-testing">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Evaluates findability of topics in a website hierarchy through text-only navigation of scenario tasks, measuring information architecture quality in isolation.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>tree-testing</tag>
      <tag>information-architecture</tag>
      <tag>ia-validation</tag>
      <tag>findability</tag>
      <tag>usability-testing</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Tree Testing</title>
    <summary>Tree testing evaluates the findability of topics in a website's hierarchy by having participants navigate a text-only version of the site structure (no design, no content) to locate answers to scenario tasks. Key metrics are success rate, directness, and first-click correctness. Requires 30-50 participants for statistical confidence and 10-15 tasks covering shallow and deep destinations.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Navigation problems found after build are expensive to fix; tree testing surfaces them before any visual work. First-click data is the most actionable signal: if first-click-correct is low even when overall success is acceptable, the IA feels wrong to users even when they eventually find the answer. Running a task leak-check (does scenario text contain the destination label?) is mandatory — LLM-generated tasks routinely leak the answer.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Validating a proposed IA before visual design or build begins.</item>
        <item>Comparing two candidate IAs head-to-head with the same task set.</item>
        <item>Post-card-sort validation: test that users can navigate the structure card sorting produced.</item>
        <item>Pre-redesign baselining: measure findability on current site vs proposed site to quantify lift.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>IA does not yet exist — run a card sort first.</item>
        <item>Testing visual labels, CTAs, or filtering UI — use first-click testing or full usability testing.</item>
        <item>Sites where &gt;50% of traffic enters via search — navigation findability is a weaker signal.</item>
        <item>Single-page apps without hierarchical navigation — there is no tree to test.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="what-it-is">
      <p>Tree testing evaluates the findability of topics in a website hierarchy by having participants navigate a text-only version of the site structure (no design, no content snippets, no search) to locate answers to scenario tasks. It isolates IA quality from visual design, content quality, and search — measuring the structure itself.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use tree testing after card sorting produces a draft IA. It validates the structure; card sorting creates it. Do not skip card sorting and go directly to tree testing on an IA designed by the team without user input.</statement>
        <rationale>Tree testing tells you if users can navigate a given structure — it does not help you discover the right structure. Testing a team-designed IA directly produces a verdict without the prior user-input that would make iteration actionable.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="key-metrics">
      <rule>
        <statement>Track four metrics per task: success rate (found correct answer — target &gt;80%), directness (found it without backtracking — target &gt;70%), first-click correctness (started in the right section), and time to complete.</statement>
        <rationale>Success rate alone is insufficient. A task with 80% success but 50% first-click-correct means users found it eventually but the IA still feels wrong — a different fix than a task with poor success and poor first-click. First click predicts 87% success when correct vs only 46% when wrong.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="tree-structure-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Cap the tree at 3-4 levels and ~100 nodes. Use actual navigation labels — no placeholder text. Match the planned structure exactly.</statement>
        <rationale>Trees deeper than 4 levels or larger than 100 nodes fatigue participants and inflate failure rates artificially. Placeholder text prevents testing the actual label vocabulary that drives real navigation behavior.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="task-writing-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Write tasks as scenarios, not as navigation instructions. The task must not contain the destination label or any word-stem overlapping the target node. Run a leak-check pass on every task before launch.</statement>
        <rationale>Tasks that echo the destination label (e.g., "Find the Returns page" when the label is "Returns") test label recognition, not information architecture. Leak-check is mandatory — even experienced researchers fail this regularly, and LLM-generated tasks almost always fail it.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Task scenario that does not reveal the destination label "Returns".</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA["You want to send back a product you ordered. Where would you go?"]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>Task that reveals the destination label directly.</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA["Find Returns" — gives away the label
"Navigate to the support section" — too directive]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="process-steps">
      <rule>
        <statement>Follow this sequence: (1) create text-only tree from IA, (2) write 10-15 scenario tasks covering shallow and deep destinations, (3) define correct and acceptable-alternative destinations per task, (4) run the test with 30-50 participants, (5) analyze per-task metrics and first-click patterns, (6) iterate and retest problem areas.</statement>
        <rationale>Skipping per-task correct-answer definition before launch produces ambiguous success scoring. Defining acceptable alternatives upfront (e.g., multiple valid locations) prevents rater disagreement and inconsistent automated scoring.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Recruit 50 participants minimum for a single-tree test; 30 per arm for an A/B comparison. Below these thresholds, success-rate confidence intervals are too wide for reliable conclusions.</statement>
        <rationale>Success rates from N=5 can vary by 40+ percentage points from the true population rate. N=30 produces confidence intervals narrow enough (~±10pp) to inform IA decisions.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="success-rate-interpretation">
      <p>Thresholds: &gt;80% — excellent, move forward; 60-80% — acceptable, minor fixes; 40-60% — problem area, needs redesign; below 40% — major issue, full redesign required.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always report per-task metrics with the worst tasks called out explicitly. Never report only the overall site average — aggregating across tasks hides the bottom 20% that require action.</statement>
        <rationale>An overall site success rate of 75% can mask 3 tasks with 30% success rates — each a blocking navigation failure. The average is a reporting artifact; the per-task breakdown is the decision input.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="path-analysis-patterns">
      <rule>
        <statement>Interpret wrong-path patterns as specific IA fixes: common wrong path = label or structure problem; random paths = label unclear; backtracking = structure does not match mental model; abandonment = content seems not to exist.</statement>
        <rationale>Each wrong-path pattern has a different root cause and a different fix. "Label confusion" → rename the label. "Random paths" → restructure or add cross-links. "Abandonment" → add the item users expected to find.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="task-design-failures">
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLM-generated tasks copy destination node labels verbatim into scenario text.</description>
        <reason>Tasks generated by agents almost always leak the destination label. The leak-check pass is mandatory for all agent-generated tasks, not optional. Run it before any human review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Including "decoy" tasks where the right answer does not exist in the tree, revealing whether participants abandon or guess confidently.</description>
        <reason>This is actually a best practice, not an antipattern. Include 2-3 decoy tasks. They expose false-confidence behavior: participants who click confidently to wrong locations even when the correct answer is absent need a different IA diagnosis than those who abandon.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="participant-and-data-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using synthetic LLM "participants" to substitute for real participant data.</description>
        <reason>LLMs roleplay tree tests by applying their own semantic priors about label relationships, not naive-user mental models. Useful only for sanity-checking task quality — never as data. Real participants are required.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Recruiting from cheap general consumer panels that inflate success rates because professional respondents click confidently and randomly.</description>
        <reason>Professional respondents who cycle through research studies produce falsely high success rates — they click confidently anywhere. Screen for category familiarity matching real users of the product.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="analysis-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Aggregating across tasks into a single "site success rate" number without per-task breakdown.</description>
        <reason>Overall site success is a reporting artifact. The decision input is per-task metrics with worst tasks highlighted. An average of 73% can hide three tasks at 30% success that each require immediate IA work.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Assuming Treejack, Maze, and UXtweak CSV exports share the same column schema.</description>
        <reason>Each tool uses different column names and success-category labels. Build provider-specific adapter functions for metric computation rather than assuming a shared schema.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="limitations">
      <p>Decontextualized: removes design, content snippets, and search — real findability is higher than tree-test scores when these are present. Task wording leaks the answer: even careful researchers accidentally use the destination label in the task. LLM-generated tasks do this routinely. Synthetic LLM "participants" can roleplay the test, but their click paths reflect the model's prior on label semantics, not real user mental models. Useful as a smoke test, not as data. Trees with &gt;100 nodes overwhelm participants and inflate failure rates artificially. Statistical confidence requires N≥30 per condition; agents that promise insights from N=5 are misusing the method.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Treat the agent as a co-author of the test, not the participant. A research agent (1) ingests the proposed IA from a sitemap/JSON, (2) generates candidate tasks scoped to user goals, (3) flags tasks whose wording leaks an answer, (4) defines correct/acceptable destinations per task, (5) configures the test in Optimal Workshop / UXtweak / Maze via API, (6) post-test, parses CSV results, computes success/directness/first-click metrics, and identifies problem areas. Real human participants run the test; the agent never substitutes for them.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-ux-researcher-agent (task design, leak-check, results synthesis); faion-content-marketer (label rewriting suggestions when "label confusion" is the root cause); faion-seo-manager (cross-checks IA against search-demand keywords (so labels match user vocabulary)); faion-product-manager (prioritizes problem areas by traffic/revenue impact).</p>
      <p>Prompt pattern for task generation: Tree: {tree_yaml} User goals (from research): {goals} Generate 12-15 tree-test tasks. For each: scenario_text, target_path, acceptable_alternate_paths. Do NOT use the destination label in scenario_text. Reject tasks that make answer obvious by phrasing.</p>
      <p>Leak check (run as second pass): For each task, list overlapping word-stems between scenario_text and target_path nodes. Flag tasks with stem overlap on the target node — those leak the answer.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Cap the tree at ~3-4 levels and ~100 nodes; deeper trees fatigue participants without producing extra signal. Write 10-15 tasks covering both shallow ("Returns" — 2 clicks) and deep ("Warranty for product X bought 2 years ago" — 4 clicks) destinations. Always include 2-3 "decoy" task types: tasks where the right answer doesn't exist in the tree, or where multiple paths are equally correct. Reveals false-confidence behavior. Recruit N=50 minimum for a single-tree test, N=30 per arm for an A/B comparison. Below this, success-rate confidence intervals are too wide. Run a leak-check pass on every task before launch; even researchers fail this regularly. Pair tree-test data with first-click analysis. A task with 80% success but 50% first-click-correct means users found it eventually but the IA still feels wrong; a task with 80% success and 80% first-click-correct is genuinely good. Re-test after iteration. Never ship IA changes off a single test cycle.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>Optimal Workshop API — Programmatic test setup, results export (https://api.optimalworkshop.com). Maze API — Test creation + results (https://help.maze.co/hc/en-us/articles/360050842554). pandas / csvkit — Compute success, directness, first-click breakdowns from exported CSVs (pip install pandas csvkit). pyvis / graphviz — Visualize wrong-path flows for stakeholder reports (pip install pyvis). xmlstarlet / yq — Convert sitemap.xml or YAML IA to tree-test format (distro / pip install yq).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <p>Optimal Workshop Treejack (SaaS, Yes — REST API): Industry standard; best analytics. UserZoom (UserTesting) (SaaS, Partial — Enterprise API): Enterprise; bundled with usability suite. UXtweak Tree Testing (SaaS, Yes — API): Generous free tier, EU data residency. Maze Tree Test (SaaS, Yes — API): Modern UI, integrates with Figma. PlaybookUX (SaaS, Partial): Affordable; smaller participant panel. Lyssna (formerly UsabilityHub) (SaaS, Partial): Includes first-click testing too. Recruitment: User Interviews / Respondent / Prolific (SaaS, Yes — APIs): Pair with any of the above for participant supply.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="references">
      <p>Spencer, Donna — Card Sorting: Designing Usable Categories (companion method). Rosenfeld, Morville, Arango — Information Architecture (4th ed.). Nielsen Norman Group — Tree Testing: https://www.nngroup.com/articles/tree-testing/. Optimal Workshop — Tree Testing 101: https://www.optimalworkshop.com/learn/101s/tree-testing/. Boxes and Arrows — Tree Testing: https://boxesandarrows.com/tree-testing/</p>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/test-plan.md" purpose="Tree test plan: objectives, tree structure, task table with correct answers, participant criteria, success criteria"/>
      <template path="templates/results-report.md" purpose="Results report: executive summary, per-task path analysis, first-click table, problem areas, recommendations"/>
      <template path="templates/metrics-parser.py" purpose="Python script: compute success rate, directness, first-click-correct from Treejack CSV export"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
